Hello all:

For an interval, we can make this loop after a period of time. However there's a problem when the body the execution function of `setInterval` takes for a long time larger than interval time. 

A typical example is:

```javascript
setInterval(()=>
{
   //Suppose this takes 2000 milliseconds
},1000);
```
Because the body of the execution function takes 2 seconds, which is larger than interval time (1 second). Sometimes this is a serious problem because the first loop hasn't been totally executed, and the next comes.

I'd like to offer a new function called `setSafeInterval`, made up of double setTimers：

```javascript
function setSafeInterval(exeFunc,intervalTime = 1000){

     let delayTime = intervalTime; 

     setTimer(function(){
               let _self = this;
    
                try{
                     exeFunc(function(){
                              setTimer(_self, delayTime);
                      });
                }catch(e){
                     //Ignore the error, we don't continue to execute the `exeFunc`.
                }
     },0);  
}
```

You can call something like this following:
```javascript

setSafeInterval(function(callBack){
//Here do what you want......
callBack(); //MUST call this for the next loop
},1000);   
```
This will make you fell comfortable to execute a function whose time is larger than the interval time safely.

What do you think of this?  I think this will solve the problem of `setInterval` and this is a common method used in many areas.

Ran into something today that I think might be a good fit for lodash.

Right now in JS, if you want to merge one array into another you have to use concat or a hacky form of `push.apply()` like `Array.prototype.push.apply([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6])`

The push.apply works fine if the second array is small, but I was working with arrays thousands of indexes long. I actually peeked into lodash's documentation to see if there was anything useful, but couldn't find anything really.

All this would do is leverage `.push()` to merge one array into another.

```
function merge(array, ...args){
    for(i in args){
        for(j in args[i]){
            array.push(args[i][j])
        }
  }
}
```

I have been working on a project where we had a serious need of deep copy. We use Lodash and there is thing called clone/cloneDeep but problem with that I found was it was just for objects ... but we also needed were arrays and more specifically array of objects

So we made a util for our internal use and now I would like to contribute to this project

Here is my Util, test version can be found at https://codepen.io/IamManchanda/pen/XYpVPY?editors=0012

```javascript
function deepCopy(value) { // deepCopy by Value
  let val;
  if (value && Array.isArray(value)) {
    val = [...value]; // Copy by Value instead of Reference - ES6 Spread
  } else if (value && typeof value === 'object') {
    val = { ...value }; // Copy by Value instead of Reference - ES6 Spread
  } else {
    return value; // Returns original value and stops!
  }

  Object.keys(val).forEach((key) => {
    if (val[key]) {
      if (Array.isArray(val[key]) || (typeof val[key] === 'object')) {
        val[key] = deepCopy(val[key]); // Recursion
      }
    }
  });
  return val; // Returns Final Value
};
```

